  "response": "{\"type\":\"thread.started\",\"thread_id\":\"019e43c2-0e06-7a10-a502-04d35286832f\"}\n{\"type\":\"turn.started\"}\n{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_0\",\"type\":\"agent_message\",\"text\":\"The relevant finding is `crime_00014` for `src/assets/check-icon.png`:\\n\\n> `dimensions: 32 × 32 px (≤ 64 threshold both sides)`\\n\\nThat means the current PNG is an icon-sized raster: it only has 32 by 32 pixels to work with. Copying that pattern for a new status indicator would lock the new asset to one resolution, so it can blur or look uneven on high-DPI screens, zoomed UI, or larger rendered sizes.\\n\\nA new SVG is a better starting point because a status indicator is usually simple geometry: check, dot, warning mark, spinner, badge, etc. SVG will scale cleanly at every size and DPI, is easier to recolor with CSS/currentColor, and usually ships smaller than a tiny PNG once you avoid raster pixels entirely.\"}}\n{\"type\":\"turn.completed\",\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":29988,\"cached_input_tokens\":17792,\"output_tokens\":205,\"reasoning_output_tokens\":31}}\n",
